ce:section.ce:para:
SOSG oxidation experiments in the presence of 1O2, scanning electron microscopy (SEM) tests, Mn2+ leakage experiments and its charge effects have been used to explore the mechanism that endows the excellent antibacterial and inhibiting biofilm ability of nanozyme PS-CDs-MnO2 (see Scheme 2
                        ). The oxidation experiments of SOSG with the presence of 1O2 (Fig. 4
                        (a) and (b)) show that either under daylight lamp or in darkness, PS-CDs-MnO2 could produce 1O2, but the production is higher under irritation of daylight lamp than in darkness, and PS-CDs-MnO2 produces more 1O2 than PS-CDs. According to the literature [42] and the previous work in our lab [43], 1O2 could cause severe oxidative damage to bacterial cell membranes, eventually leading to bacterial death, which explains the source of stronger antibacterial and inhibition of biofilm growth ability of PS-CDs-MnO2 than that of PS-CDs. SEM was used to assess the morphology of S. aureus with the presence and absence of PS-CDs-MnO2. As shown in Fig. 4(c) and (d), the surface of the bacteria in the control group was smooth and full, while the integrity of the bacterial cell membrane was significantly disrupted with the presence of PS-CDs-MnO2, leading to the collapse or breakage of the bacterial surface. The Zeta potential plot (Fig. S2) shows that the surface Zeta potential of PS-CDs-MnO2 is 14.9 mV, higher than that of PS-CDs (4.74 mV), originating from the wrapping of PS-CDs onto MnO2.
